      <exercise>
       <statement>
          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

            <p>
              Use vector addition to determine the point that is three-sevenths of the way from the point <m>(-6,-4)</m> to the point <m>(3,-2)</m> along the line segment that connects the two points.
            </p>

            <figure xml:id="trigonometry-vectors-exercises-figure-4">
              <caption>Determine the Coordinates of the Point <m>(x_1,y_1)</m></caption>
              <image>
                <description>
                  Solid dots at the points at the points <m>(-6,-4)</m> and <m>(3,-2)</m> along with the line segments connecting the two points.  There is also a solid dot on the line segment labeled <m>(x_1,y_1)</m>.  That point is three-sevenths of the way from <m>(-6,-4)</m> to <m>(3,-2)</m> and lies in Quadrant III.   
                </description>
                <latex-image>
                  <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                      \begin{axis} [axis equal image,
                                    xmin=-8,xmax=4,
                                    ymin=-8,ymax=4,
                                    xtick={-6,-4,-2,2,4,6},
                                    ytick={-6,-4,-2,2,4,6},
                                    minor xtick={-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7},
                                    minor ytick={-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7}]
                        \addplot[soliddot,color=black] coordinates {(-6,-4)};
                        \addplot[soliddot,color=black] coordinates {(3,-2)};
                        \addplot[soliddot,color=red] coordinates {(-2.14,-3.14)} node[below] {$(x_1,y_1)$};
                        \addplot[interval,ultra thick,blue,-] coordinates {(-6,-4) (3,-2)}; 
                      \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                  ]]>
                </latex-image>
              </image>
            </figure>

          </sidebyside>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

            <p>
              The component form of the vector from the point <m>(-6,4)</m> to the point <m>(3,-2)</m> is determined below.
              <me>\langle 3-(-6),-2-(-4) \rangle=\langle 9,2 \rangle</me>
              See <xref ref="trigonometry-vectors-exercises-figure-4-soultion">Figure</xref> to follow the logic to the solution presented below.
            </p>

            <figure xml:id="trigonometry-vectors-exercises-figure-4-soultion">
              <caption>Determine the Coordinates of the Point <m>(x_1,y_1)</m></caption>
              <image>
                <description>
                  There is a vector drawn from the origin to the point <m>(-6,-4)</m> and a vector drawn from the point <m>(-6,-4)</m> to the point <m>(3,-2)</m>.  Superimposed over the second vector is a vector from the point <m>(-6,-4)</m> to a point labeled <m>(x_1,y_1)</m>.  The superimposed vector ends in Quadrant III and is three-sevenths as long as the vector from the point <m>(-6,-4)</m> to the point <m>(3,-2)</m>.  Finally, the is a vector drawn from the origin to the point labeled <m>(x_1,y_1)</m>.
                </description>
                <latex-image>
                  <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                      \begin{axis} [axis equal image,
                                    xmin=-8,xmax=4,
                                    ymin=-8,ymax=4,
                                    xtick={-6,-4,-2,2},
                                    ytick={-6,-4,-2,2},
                                    minor xtick={-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7},
                                    minor ytick={-7,-5,-3,-1,1,3,5,7}]
                        \addplot[soliddot,color=red] coordinates {(-2.14,-3.14)} node[below] {$(x_1,y_1)$};
                        \addplot[interval,ultra thick,blue,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(-6,-4) (3,-2)};
                        \addplot[interval,ultra thick,red,dashed,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(-6,-4) (-2.14,-3.14)};
                        \addplot[interval,ultra thick,green!30!brown,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(0,0) (-6,-4)};
                        \addplot[interval,ultra thick,red!30!blue,-{Stealth}] coordinates {(0,0) (-2.14,-3.14)};  
                      \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                  ]]>
                </latex-image>
              </image>
            </figure>

          </sidebyside>
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>\langle x_1,y_1\rangle\amp=\langle -6,-4 \rangle + \frac{3}{7}\langle 9,2 \rangle</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\langle -6,-4 \rangle + \left\langle \frac{3}{7}(9),\frac{3}{7}(2) \right\rangle</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\langle -6,-4 \rangle + \left\langle \frac{27}{7},\frac{6}{7}\right\rangle</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\left\langle -6+\frac{27}{7},-4+\frac{6}{7}\right\rangle</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\left\langle -\frac{15}{7},-\frac{22}{7}\right\rangle</mrow>
            </md>
            The point three-sevenths of the way from the point <m>(-6,4)</m> to the point <m>(3,-2)</m> is <m>\left(-\frac{15}{7},\frac{10}{7}\right)</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

